article.headline: LSU 95, Georgia 79
article.story: ATHENS, Ga. (AP) -- Coming off his worst game of the season, the last thing on Antonio Hudson's mind was setting a career high in scoring. In fact, the Louisiana State senior still didn't know after Wednesday night's game that his 26 points in a 95-79 win over Georgia set a new personal high. "Playing basketball, you go through ups and downs," Hudson said. "When you have people in your corner, it makes it easier on you as a player. I still had the support of my team." Hudson, held to a season-low three points in LSU's win over Mississippi State Saturday, bounced back to top his previous high of 25 points against South Carolina on March 12, 2004. Hudson, who hit four 3-pointers, helped the Tigers claim their first win at Georgia in 14 years and their first Southeastern Conference road win of the season. "Hudson had a real good game," said LSU coach John Brady. "In order to win on the road, sometimes you have to have guys step up and score points." Brandon Bass, last week's Southeastern Conference Player of the Week, added 21 points and Darrel Mitchell had 17 for LSU. The Tigers won at Stegeman Coliseum for the first time since 1991. Georgia, held to 47 points in each of its losses to Florida and Alabama last week, lost despite scoring its most points since a 100-69 win over Savannah State on Dec. 28. "We did better offensively," said Georgia coach Dennis Felton. "It's frustrating to score about 80 points and still lose the game, but we did because we gave up 95. They are a hard team to stop if their guards are shooting well from 3s, and they were." LSU (12-6 overall, 5-2 SEC) has won six of its last seven, including three straight. Georgia (7-11 overall, 1-7 SEC) has three straight losses since its only conference win against Vanderbilt on Jan. 22. Channing Toney led Georgia with 18 points. Levi Stukes added 16 and Steve Newman had 14. LSU led 50-42 at halftime despite Georgia's 7-of-11 3-point shooting. "The way they shot the ball in the first half, we looked at it like it couldn't get any worse," Hudson said. "To Georgia's credit, they played a great first half," Brady said. "We had to play better defense in the second half, and we did." Georgia's first five field goals of the game were 3-pointers -- four by Toney and one by Stukes. But even with the strong outside shooting, Georgia couldn't keep pace with LSU's better balance. The Tigers almost matched Georgia with six 3-pointers and had the inside advantage with 6-foot-8 Bass and 6-foot-9, 310-pound freshman Glen Davis. Davis had 12 points and 11 rebounds, his sixth straight game with 10 or more rebounds. Each team finished the game with nine 3-pointers. An 11-0 run gave the Tigers an 18-6 lead, but Georgia stayed close with its 3-point shooting. There were five ties before Hudson scored eight of LSU's final 12 points of the half. LSU opened the second half with a jam by Bass, followed by a 3-pointer from Hudson. The Tigers kept the lead in double figures most of the second half, though a three-point play by Younes Idrissi cut the deficit to seven points with 10:16 left. LSU led by 15 or more points the last five minutes. LSU outrebounded Georgia 36-27. Georgia, which starts three guards, had been outrebounded by an average of 42-26 in its previous four games. Dominique Wilkins, the only Georgia player to have his jersey retired, attended the game. Wilkins now is a vice president with the Atlanta Hawks.
